Here's a breakdown of the relationship between EXPTIME-complete and the more familiar complexity classes P, NP, and NP-complete, focusing on their relative difficulty and containment:

  1. The Fundamental Hierarchy: Time Complexity

    • P (Polynomial Time): Problems solvable by a deterministic Turing machine in time polynomial to the input size (n^k for some constant k). Represents problems considered "efficiently solvable" classically.

    • NP (Nondeterministic Polynomial Time): Problems where a proposed solution (a "certificate") can be verified by a deterministic Turing machine in polynomial time. Includes problems like Boolean Satisfiability (SAT) and the Traveling Salesman decision problem. P ⊆ NP (if you can solve it, you can obviously verify a solution).

    • EXPTIME (Exponential Time): Problems solvable by a deterministic Turing machine in time exponential to the input size (2^{n^k} for some constant k). This is a much larger class than P or NP.

  2. Key Containment Relationships:

    • P ⊆ NP ⊆ PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME ⊆ EXPSPACE ⊆ ...

    • Crucially, NP ⊆ EXPTIME. Any problem verifiable in polynomial time is also solvable in exponential time (by brute-forcing all possible certificates).

    • Furthermore, PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME. Problems solvable with polynomial memory can also be solved in exponential time (though potentially using much more memory than PSPACE requires).

  3. EXPTIME-Completeness:

    • A problem is EXPTIME-hard if every problem in EXPTIME can be reduced to it in polynomial time.

    • A problem is EXPTIME-complete if it is both:

      1. In EXPTIME: Solvable in exponential time.

      2. EXPTIME-hard: Every other problem in EXPTIME can be efficiently (poly-time) reduced to it.

    • EXPTIME-complete problems are the hardest problems within EXPTIME.

  4. Comparison to NP and NP-Complete:

    • NP ⊆ EXPTIME: This means every NP problem (including NP-complete problems like SAT) is also in EXPTIME.

    • NP-complete vs. EXPTIME-complete: An NP-complete problem is among the hardest problems within NP. An EXPTIME-complete problem is among the hardest problems within EXPTIME, which is a vastly larger class.

    • Strict Separation (Proven!): Unlike the famous unproven P vs NP question, it is proven that P ⊂ EXPTIME. There are problems in EXPTIME that cannot be solved in polynomial time. This implies:

      • EXPTIME-complete problems are provably harder than P.

      • EXPTIME-complete problems are provably harder than NP-complete problems (since NP-complete problems are in NP, and NP ⊆ EXPTIME, but EXPTIME-complete problems are not in P, while NP-complete problems might be in P if P=NP - though this is believed false).

      • Solving an EXPTIME-complete problem in the worst case requires exponential time on any deterministic Turing machine (and by the Church-Turing thesis, any classical computer).

  5. Practical Implications & Examples:

    • Intractability: EXPTIME-complete problems are fundamentally intractable for large inputs. While NP-complete problems might have efficient solutions for many real-world instances or benefit from heuristics, EXPTIME-complete problems quickly become unsolvable for even moderately sized inputs as the required time literally explodes exponentially.

    • Examples: Classic EXPTIME-complete problems often involve perfect play in complex games with exponential decision trees:

      • Generalized Chess/Go/Checkers: Determining if a player can force a win from a given n x n board position (with specific generalized rulesets).

      • Succinct Graph Problems: Problems where the input graph is described extremely concisely (e.g., by a circuit or formula), allowing an exponentially large graph to be represented with a polynomial description. Checking properties like reachability on such succinctly represented graphs becomes EXPTIME-complete.

      • Certain Problems in Logic & Formal Verification: Problems like deciding the truth of formulas in certain powerful logics (e.g., some modal logics with fixed points) or equivalence checking for succinctly described systems.

You've hit on a crucial subtlety in complexity theory! Here's a clear breakdown of the relationships:

  1. Space vs. Time Hierarchies:

    • PSPACE: Problems solvable with polynomial space (time can be exponential).

    • EXPTIME: Problems solvable with exponential time (space can be exponential).

    • EXPSPACE: Problems solvable with exponential space (time can be double-exponential or worse).

  2. Containment Relationships:

    • PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME: True. Any poly-space computation can use at most exponential time before repeating a configuration. So, all PSPACE problems are in EXPTIME.

    • EXPTIME ⊆ EXPSPACE: True. An exponential-time computation can only use exponential space (it can't write more than exponential bits in exponential time). So, all EXPTIME problems are in EXPSPACE.

    • PSPACE ⊂ EXPSPACE: Proven strict! (By the space hierarchy theorem). There are problems solvable in exponential space but not in polynomial space.

    • EXPTIME ⊂ EXPTIME: Proven strict! (By the time hierarchy theorem). There are problems solvable in exponential time but not in polynomial time. This also implies P ⊂ EXPTIME and NP ⊂ EXPTIME.

  3. EXPSPACE vs. EXPTIME:

    • EXPTIME ⊆ EXPSPACE (as above).

    • EXPSPACE ⊈ EXPTIME: Proven strict! (By the time hierarchy theorem applied to EXPTIME). There are problems solvable in exponential space that require more than exponential time. These problems are in EXPSPACE but not in EXPTIME.

    • Relationship: EXPTIME is a strict subset of EXPSPACE. There is a hierarchy: P ⊆ PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME ⊂ EXPSPACE ⊂ 2-EXPTIME ⊂ 2-EXPSPACE ⊂ ...

  4. Properties of EXPSPACE:

    • Massively Intractable: Problems require exponential space and often double-exponential time or worse. Even more fundamentally infeasible than EXPTIME or PSPACE-complete problems.

    • EXPSPACE-Complete Problems: Exist and are the hardest problems in EXPSPACE. Classic examples involve:

      • Succinct Versions of Hard Problems: Verifying properties of circuits or formulas that succinctly encode exponentially large structures. For example:

        • Succinct Reachability: Does node t in a graph represented by a tiny (poly-size) circuit describing its adjacency matrix reach node s? The graph itself has exponential size.

        • Equivalence of Regular Expressions with Squaring (e.g., (a+b)* vs. (a*+b*)* is easy, but ((a+b)^n)^* vs. other expressions becomes EXPSPACE-complete).

      • Certain Formal Verification Problems: Model checking for complex systems specified very compactly.

      • Deciding Truth in Powerful Logics: Like Presburger arithmetic with exponentiation.

The questions of whether BQP = PSPACE or whether BQP is PSPACE-hard are central open problems in quantum complexity theory. Here’s a concise breakdown based on current knowledge:

1. Could BQP = PSPACE?

  • Status: Strongly conjectured false (but not proven).

  • Evidence:

    • BQP ⊆ PSPACE is proven (quantum circuits can be simulated classically in polynomial space).

    • PSPACE ⊆ BQP? If true, quantum computers could efficiently solve all PSPACE problems (including NP-complete, #P, etc.). This is considered unlikely.

    • Oracle separations: Relative to certain oracles, PSPACE ⊄ BQP (evidence against equality).

    • PP ⊆ PSPACE, but PP ⊄ BQP relative to an oracle (Aaronson, 2010).

  • Implication: If BQP = PSPACE, quantum computers would efficiently solve problems like True Quantified Boolean Formulas (TQBF) (PSPACE-complete), which is believed intractable even for quantum machines.

2. Could BQP be PSPACE-hard?

  • Status: Conjectured false (and would imply BQP = PSPACE).

  • Reasoning:

    • If BQP were PSPACE-hard, then PSPACE ⊆ BQP. Since BQP ⊆ PSPACE, this would force BQP = PSPACE.

    • Proving BQP is PSPACE-hard requires showing every PSPACE problem reduces to a BQP problem. No such reduction is known.

  • Consequence: PSPACE-hardness of BQP would mean quantum computers efficiently solve all PSPACE-complete problems, which is considered implausible.

Complexity classes in computer science are already well-understood. Quantum computers are very difficult to build, but we have a very strong understanding of their capabilities. It's the other way around from the normal assumption: quantum computing does not generally make things faster. In fact, for most applications it's strictly worse, since it can't even deterministically return the correct result. Quantum computing is superior to classical computing only when the algorithm in question falls into a quantum complexity class. There are some very important algorithms that are good candidates for quantum computation, like prime factorization and searching unsorted databases, but we can show that go is not inside one of the complexity classes that benefit from quantum computing. It's too high on the hierarchy of complexity. Long explanation below. The following explanation is a simplification and is not fully technically precise, but it is approximately correct: We have notation which describes the way the required computation increases as a function of input size. For example, naively searching a list of elements by stepping through it one at a time has a worst-case complexity of O(n), since it takes at most a number of steps which linearly increases with the input size. The naive search is O(n) regardless of whether the list is sorted. However, in a binary search, you just continually cut the list in half in the correct direction until you find the element you're looking for. For example, let's say the element we're looking for is the 65th element in a list of 100. We don't know the location, but we know what value we're searching the list for. we would first check element 50. It's too low, so now we check element 75. That would be too high, so now we check element 62 (in between 50 and 75, doesn't matter which way you round I believe). 62 is too low, so we check element 68 (halfway between 62 and 75). That's too high, so we check element 65. This turns out to be the correct one. We found it in 5 steps, while the naive search would take 65 steps to get to element 65. If you had ten hours of video footage and you wanted to identify the exact moment a bicycle was stolen, you could find the exact second of theft pretty quickly with a binary search (much faster than just watching that footage, even on fast forward). Binary search has a worst-case complexity of O(log n), which means that each time you multiply the input by 10, you only double the computation required. 1000x larger? Only 8x more computation. However, notably, binary search only works on sorted lists, so if the list is unsorted, we have to do that first, and each sorting algorithm has different properties (typically we care about average-case computation, worst-case computation, and auxiliary space needed to store intermediate computations). Also, while some kinds of lists can be easily sorted (numbers by value, strings in alphabetic order), other kinds of lists may resist sorting, like lists which contain disparate data types. As you can imagine, complexity matters a lot for programmers working with large amounts of data, since doing good software engineering and selecting the right algorithms for sorting/search/etc can lead to *ridiculous* improvements in speed. Ever wonder why Google can return a search page in a fraction of a second? It's because better programmers can get better performance. Two very important classical complexity classes are P and NP. Algorithms in P can be computed in polynomial time (which in most cases means they are efficiently computable), but algorithms in NP cannot be computed in polynomial time (the amount of computation required to find the solution grows *absurdly rapidly* as the input size increases). However, solutions to NP problems can be *verified* in polynomial time. The classic example of an NP problem is prime factorization. A semiprime is a number with only two prime factors. If I give you a semiprime with a hundred thousand digits, no computer on earth could find the two prime factors in any reasonable amount of time. However, if I gave you one of the two primes, you could easily find the other one with simple division. If I gave you both, you could simply multiply them and verify that they are the correct solution (they are the factors of that semiprime). The fact that you can *verify* solutions to NP problems but cannot *solve* NP problems is important for things like RSA cryptography, which is critical for security on the Internet -- if you don't already have a key that can decrypt the cipher, finding some such key with a classical computer is basically impossible. In public-key cryptography like RSA, the first user encrypts data using a public key that only the second user's private key can decrypt, and the second user responds by encrypting data with a public key that only the first user's private key can decrypt. As long as my private key is kept secure, any ciphertext encrypted with the corresponding public key is unbreakable unless you can efficiently do prime factorization of very large semiprimes, which classical computers cannot do. Even if classical computers get fast enough to attempt it (they cannot, due to physical limits), we could just increase the key size. Doubling the key size increases the encryption/decryption time by a factor of five to ten, but verifying answers to NP problems is relatively easy. A speed decrease of ten times is very annoying, so we want to use the lowest secure RSA key size, but doubling the key size increases the security of the encryption exponentially against attackers who do not have the private key. Now we introduce quantum computers. Quantum complexity classes are not the same as classical complexity classes because quantum computers do a radically different kind of computation. (Simplified: quantum computation is incredibly parallel and can do multiple operations simultaneously. Quantum computers use superposition and entanglement to do this.) The relevant quantum complexity class here is BQP, in which problems can be solved in polynomial time with at most an error rate of 1/3 (all quantum computations have an error rate since they are non-deterministic, but if you can prove a sufficiently low error rate, you can just run it again if the answer doesn't work). Prime factorization is in BQP. Unlike a classical computer, which cannot hope to efficiently find prime factors, quantum computers have an algorithm called Shor's algorithm which does efficiently find prime factors. Shor's algorithm does not always return the correct answer, but assuming a high-quality quantum computer, the distribution of outputs spikes hard enough at the correct answer that the output (randomly selected along that distribution) should be the right answer almost every time. Unfortunately, quantum computers get even more difficult to build as they get larger since qubits (which do all of the computation) are delicate quantum objects. Environmental noise can decohere qubits, which breaks the quantum computer. IBM currently has the largest quantum computer with 1,121 qubits, and they are nowhere near perfectly reliable. To break RSA-2048, which is a pretty standard and secure form of encryption, you would need a few thousand perfect qubits. With current qubits, we would need many levels of error correction and redundancy. Breaking RSA-2048 would require twenty million qubits according to a paper from 2019. Certainly this number is lower in 2025, but we are nowhere near. While this sounds like a high bar (because it is), it's important to consider that breaking RSA-2048 with a classical computer takes something like 300 trillion years. Each doubling of the key size makes it about ten times for annoying for the users, but about a billion times more difficult to crack, adding nine zeroes to your compute time with each doubling. Meanwhile, because BQP problems grow polynomially (n^2) rather than exponentially (2^n) like NP problems, increasing the key size only makes it moderately more difficult for a sufficiently capable quantum computer. To sum up, quantum computers are not just classical computers but more powerful. They're worse in almost every way. They're more difficult to set up, they're more difficult to keep running effectively, they're much more expensive, they output false answers with some regularity, and so on. It's hilariously impractical to use a quantum computer for anything that can be efficiently done by a classical computer. Most problems which are intractable for classical computers (like solving go or chess) are also intractable for quantum systems, since solving these games is in a higher complexity class. The classical classes P and NP and the quantum class BQP are inside a larger class called PSPACE, which defines all problems which can be solved with a polynomial amount of memory. The extra powers afforded to quantum computers (BQP) compared to classical computers (P, NP) do not help for problems which are not in BQP, so for all problems in PSPACE that are not inside the nested BQP class, quantum computers provide no shortcuts or advantages in computation. In fact, all we have to do to prove that quantum computation does not help is to show that a given problem is not in the BQP class (or any other quantum complexity class). Is go in PSPACE? No, of course not lol, that would be too easy! EXPTIME is the class of problems which can be solved in exponential time. Since all problems that can be solved in polynomial space can also be solved in exponential time (although it may require exponential space to do it this way), EXPTIME contains PSPACE. EXPTIME is an extremely difficult complexity class, since the required computation grows exponentially as the input size grows -- EXPTIME problems are usually considered computationally intractable except at very small input sizes. Solving EXPTIME problems beyond trivial size is very difficult. So, is go in EXPTIME? Nope! Go is EXPTIME-complete, which is the class for the hardest problems in EXPTIME (the various -complete classes have a lot of other interesting properties not worth going into here). Go is *unfathomably complex*. It will *never* be solved. tl;dr Quantum computers are only superior for specific algorithms which fall into quantum complexity classes. Go has been proven to not fall into one of those classes. Quantum computers are not useful for solving go, and do not help at solving a great deal of other computational problems. Congrats, if you read this far you now know more about computational complexity than most CS graduates. Some notes: Many of the subset relations mentioned above are still subject to open questions. For example, while we can trivially prove that P is a subset of NP, it remains an open question whether P and NP are actually the *same* set. You can get a million dollar prize if you prove it either way! If P = NP, then classical computers can do prime factorization and other NP problems in polynomial time. We have no proof either way, but I don't know a single person who believes P = NP. Also, while go with Japanese ko rules is in EXPTIME-complete, go without ko is in PSPACE-hard (still too hard for quantum computers, since BQP is inside PSPACE), and nobody knows what the complexity of go with superko is. Applying a superko rule to games like chess puts them in EXPSPACE-complete, which is an *outrageously* complex class, but apparently this doesn't happen with superko go -- instead, the addition of superko removes both the upper and lower bounds from the the Japanese ko difficulty, so we don't have a damn clue (although it has to be at least PSPACE-hard by analogy with go without ko.) As a fun nuance, it isn't actually proven that BQP doesn't equal PSPACE. So it is within the realm of technical possibility that a quantum computer could solve PSPACE-hard problems like go without- ko, but it's about as likely as finding a live unicorn in your backyard -- it's just not technically ruled out. As a fun grenade for anyone still reading, all of the above discussion is about *generalized go*, which is played on any n x n sized board. There are slightly difference consequences when talking about fixed board sizes, since it opens the option of simply brute forcing all possible games from that board size. 19x19 go is almost certainly in PSPACE along with the other fixed-size games. This is much, much easier than EXPTIME-complete, but you could not fit such a computer in this universe since it would require more bits of memory than this universe has particles -- and in any case, fixed board sizes aren't in BQP either. Quantum computers don't solve the complexity problem, although quantum algorithms might reduce the amount of computation required to brute force the full solution. For example, Grover's algorithm is a quantum algorithm that, if applicable, would give a quadratic speedup to the brute force process. Unfortunately, the square root of 10^170 (the approximate search space of go) is still 10^85. There are estimated to be 10^80 protons and neutrons in the universe, and if we inscribed one go position on each such proton and neutron, we would need 100,000 universes like our own just for storage.

Corrections & Clarifications

    • BQP ⊆ PSPACE is proven.

    • EXPTIME-complete ⊈ BQP is not proven but strongly conjectured (via oracle separations and hierarchy theorems).

    • Critical nuance: Even if BQP ≠ PSPACE, quantum computers could offer speedups for subroutines of EXPTIME-complete problems (e.g., heuristic search), but no such algorithm exists for Go.

  4. Grover’s Algorithm for Fixed-Board Go:

  5. NP vs. EXPTIME:

    • NP ⊆ PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME, but NP ≠ EXPTIME (proven).

You've hit on a crucial distinction: strong play versus game-theoretic solving. Classical heuristics (like MCTS + neural networks) create unbeatable players, but they cannot mathematically solve Go. Here's why:

1. Solving Requires Proof, Not Just Performance

  • To solve a game, you must prove the game-theoretic value (win/loss/draw) of every possible position under perfect play. This requires:

    • Exhaustive analysis: Certifying outcomes for all ~10¹⁷⁰ positions.

    • Optimality guarantees: A proof that no better move exists in any position.

  • AlphaGo/AlphaZero approximate optimal play but cannot provide proofs. They:

    • Prune the game tree heuristically (missing rare critical lines).

    • Use neural networks trained on human/data-driven play (inherently incomplete).

    • Have no mechanism to certify "no better move exists."

2. How Games Are Actually Solved

  • Brute-force + combinatorial optimization (e.g., Checkers, Connect Four):

    • Build an endgame database backward from terminal states.

    • Propagate proven values up the game tree.

  • For Go, this fails catastrophically:

    • The branching factor is ~250 per move (vs. 8 for Checkers).

    • The full tree has ~10³⁶⁰ nodes (vs. 10²⁰ for Checkers).

    • Storage requirement: ~10¹⁵⁰ bytes (vs. 10¹⁴ bytes for Checkers).
      (The observable universe has ~10⁸⁰ atoms.)

3. Why Heuristics Don't Solve Go

MethodPurposeFails at Solving Because...
MCTSSmart exploration of high-value movesExplores < 0.0001% of the tree; no completeness.
Neural NetworksPredict win% & move qualityGeneralizes from data; cannot prove correctness.
Hybrids (AlphaZero)Balance strength & efficiencyStill probabilistic and approximate.

4. Could We Solve Go Classically?

  • Theoretically: Yes, 19×19 Go is finite → technically in O(1) complexity class.

  • Practically: Physically impossible with known physics:

    • Time: > 10¹⁰⁰ years (even at 1 move/Planck time).

    • Space: Storing position values requires more atoms than exist.

    • Energy: Running such a computer would exceed the universe's energy.

5. Quantum Computers Don't Help

  • Grover's algorithm: At best, reduces search to √(10¹⁷⁰) = 10⁸⁵ operations.

    • Still requires 10⁵× more resources than exist in the universe.

  • No known quantum algorithm can replace combinatorial proof methods.

Conclusion

Classical heuristics create strong agents, not solutions. Solving Go would require:

  1. A computational miracle (e.g., a breakthrough in abstract game representation), or

  2. Accepting that Go is "solved" only in the weak sense (e.g., "Humans + AIs agree Black wins by 6.5 points with perfect komi").

The relationship between BQP (quantum polynomial time) and NP (nondeterministic polynomial time) is a major open question in complexity theory. Here's a precise breakdown:

1. Known Containments & Separations

  • BQP ⊆ PSPACE
    Quantum computations can be classically simulated with polynomial space (but may require exponential time).

  • NP ⊆ PSPACE
    NP problems can be solved with polynomial space (e.g., via brute-force search).

  • P ⊆ NP ∩ BQP
    Problems efficiently solvable classically (P) are also in NP and BQP.

2. Key Overlaps

  • Factoring: Shor’s algorithm solves integer factoring in BQP, and factoring is in NP (and coNP).

  • Graph Isomorphism: Suspected to be in NP-intermediate (neither NP-complete nor in P), and has known quantum speedups (though not proven BQP).

3. Critical Unknowns

  • Does NP ⊆ BQP?

    • If yes, quantum computers could solve all NP problems (including NP-complete ones) efficiently.

    • Status: Strongly conjectured false. No evidence suggests quantum computers can solve NP-complete problems (e.g., SAT, Traveling Salesman) in polynomial time.

  • Does BQP ⊆ NP?

    • Unlikely: BQP contains problems like the discrete logarithm, which are not known to be in NP.

  • Does BQP = NP?

    • Widely believed false—BQP and NP likely represent distinct computational realms.

4. Oracle Evidence

  • Relative to certain "black boxes" (oracles):

    • NP ⊄ BQP (there exist oracles where NP problems resist quantum speedups).

    • BQP ⊄ NP (oracles exist where quantum problems cannot be verified classically in NP-time).

5. Practical Implications

  • NP-complete problems (e.g., SAT, protein folding) likely cannot be solved efficiently by quantum computers.

  • Quantum advantage is known only for specific problems:

    • Factoring/discrete log (BQP ∩ NP).

    • Quantum simulation (BQP \ NP).

    • Unstructured search (O(√N) via Grover, but only quadratic speedup).

Visual Summary:

   /      \

  \        /
   \      /
     P ⊆ NP ∩ BQP

Where:
- "⊆" = contained in
- "∩" = overlap (e.g., factoring)
- "\\" = no known containment

Conclusion

  • BQP and NP likely overlap but neither contains the other.

  • NP-complete problems are almost certainly not in BQP—quantum computers won't efficiently solve SAT, chess, or optimal Go.

  • If NP ⊆ BQP were true, it would imply P = NP (via BQP ⊆ PSPACE), upending cryptography and optimization. This is deemed extremely unlikely.

Here's a precise breakdown of the relationships, addressing both your questions:

1. P ⊆ NP and P ⊆ BQP

  • P ⊆ NP:
    Any problem solvable in polynomial time by a deterministic classical computer (P) can be verified in polynomial time by re-running the solver.
    Example: Sorting a list (P). Verification: Check if the list is sorted (trivial).

  • P ⊆ BQP:
    Quantum computers can efficiently simulate classical computations. Any classical polynomial-time algorithm can be executed on a quantum computer with at most polynomial overhead.
    Example: Finding shortest paths (P) can be solved on a quantum computer with similar efficiency.

  • NP: Problems where "YES" instances have short, verifiable proofs.

  • coNP: Problems where "NO" instances have short, verifiable proofs.
    Example: UNSAT – a proof of unsatisfiability (e.g., a resolution refutation) proves no satisfying assignment exists.

2. **Why does NP ≠ coNP imply P ≠ NP?**

- We use contrapositive reasoning: show that if P = NP, then NP = coNP.

- If P = NP, then every problem in NP is solvable in polynomial time (P).

- For any problem in coNP, its complement is in NP. Since NP = P, the complement is in P, so the original problem is also in P (and thus in NP). Hence coNP ⊆ NP.

- Similarly, NP ⊆ coNP (because if a problem is in NP, its complement is in coNP, and by the same reasoning, the complement is in P, hence in NP? Actually, we need symmetry).

- More carefully: if P = NP, then for any language L ∈ coNP, its complement L' is in NP. But NP = P, so L' ∈ P. Since P is closed under complement, L ∈ P. Then L ∈ NP (because P ⊆ NP). Thus coNP ⊆ NP.

- Conversely, for any language L ∈ NP, since NP = P, L ∈ P. Then L' (complement) is in P (closed under complement) and thus in NP (since P ⊆ NP). But L' ∈ NP implies L ∈ coNP. Thus NP ⊆ coNP.

- Therefore, NP = coNP.

- By contrapositive: if NP ≠ coNP, then P ≠ NP.

Proof sketch:

  2. Let L be any problem in coNP.

    • By definition: If input x ∉ L, there exists a short proof refuting x (verifiable in poly-time).

    • If L‾∈P\overline{L} \in \textbf{P}L∈P, then L∈PL \in \textbf{P}L∈P.

  6. Thus, L ∈ P ⊆ NP.

  7. Conclusion: Every coNP problem is in NP → NP = coNP.

Contrapositive:

If NP ≠ coNP, then P ≠ NP.

Intuition:

  • If NP ≠ coNP, finding proofs for NO is fundamentally harder → P ≠ NP.

The "cage logic" applies selectively in complexity theory—it depends on proven containment chains and hierarchy theorems. Here's when it holds and when it doesn't:

When Containment is a "Cage" (Proven Barriers)

  1. BQP ⊆ PSPACE

    • Why a cage: PSPACE is provably contained in EXPTIME (PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME), and the Time Hierarchy Theorem proves EXPTIME ⊊ 2-EXPTIME.

    • Thus: BQP ⊆ PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME ⊊ 2-EXPTIME
      → Quantum computers cannot solve EXPTIME-complete problems (e.g., generalized Go), even if BQP = PSPACE.

  2. NP ⊆ PSPACE

    • Same principle: NP ⊆ PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME
      → Classical or quantum computers cannot solve EXPTIME-complete problems in polynomial time.

  3. P ⊆ NP

    • While P vs. NP is open, P ⊆ PH ⊆ PSPACE (where PH = Polynomial Hierarchy).
      → If a problem is PSPACE-hard (e.g., true quantified Boolean formulas), it cannot be solved in polynomial time even if P = NP.

When Containment is Not a Cage (Open Equality Cases)

  1. P vs. NP

    • P ⊆ NP, but no proven separation:

      • If P = NP, NP-complete problems become tractable.

      • If P ≠ NP, NP-complete problems remain intractable.

    • Not a cage: We lack a hierarchy-based barrier like PSPACE/EXPTIME.

  2. NP vs. coNP

    • NP ⊆ PSPACE and coNP ⊆ PSPACE, but no proven separation between NP/coNP and P/PSPACE.

    • Not a cage: If NP = coNP, it wouldn't contradict existing hierarchy theorems.

  3. BPP vs. P

    • BPP (bounded-error probabilistic poly-time) contains P, but BPP ⊆ P is conjectured (i.e., randomness doesn't help).

    • Not a cage: No higher-class barrier forces separation.

The "Cage" Principle Summarized

A containment A ⊆ B acts as a computational "cage" only if:

  1. B is separated from a higher class C (via hierarchy theorems), and

  2. Problems in C \ B exist and are proven intractable for A.

Why BQP ⊆ PSPACE is Special

  • PSPACE has a proven "ceiling":
    PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME ⊊ 2-EXPTIME ⊊ ...
    → Anything ⊆ PSPACE (BQP, NP, P, etc.) is caged below EXPTIME-hard problems.

Practical Implications

  • Quantum computers are caged: They can't solve EXPTIME-complete problems (e.g., optimal play in generalized board games).

  • Classical computers are caged: Even if P = NP, they can't solve PSPACE-hard problems in polynomial time.

  • Unknowns persist: Cages only exist where hierarchy theorems force separations.

In essence: Containment becomes a "cage" when a proven upward separation (like PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME) creates an unreachable class above. For open questions like P vs. NP, no such barrier exists—so the cage logic does not apply universally.

We are discussing computational complexity theory, specifically why quantum computers (modeled by the class BQP) cannot solve EXPTIME-complete problems, even in principle (ignoring physical constraints).

Key points from our prior discussion:

1. **BQP ⊆ PSPACE**: This is a proven containment. Any problem solvable by a quantum computer in polynomial time can be solved by a classical computer using polynomial space (but possibly exponential time).

2. **PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME**: This is also proven. Problems solvable in polynomial space can be solved in exponential time (because a polynomial-space bounded Turing machine has a finite number of configurations, and thus runs in at most exponential time).

3. **EXPTIME-complete problems are hard**: These are the hardest problems in EXPTIME. By definition, if a problem is EXPTIME-complete, then every problem in EXPTIME can be reduced to it in polynomial time.

Now, the critical separation:

- **PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME**: This is proven by the time hierarchy theorem. Specifically, the time hierarchy theorem states that with more time, you can solve strictly more problems. Since PSPACE problems can be solved in exponential time (PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME) but there are problems in EXPTIME that require exponential time and cannot be solved in polynomial space (by the space hierarchy theorem and the relationship between time and space), we have PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME.

Therefore, since:

BQP ⊆ PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME

it follows that BQP ⊊ EXPTIME.

In particular, EXPTIME-complete problems are not in PSPACE (because if they were, then since PSPACE is closed under polynomial-time reductions, we would have EXPTIME ⊆ PSPACE, contradicting PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME). Therefore, EXPTIME-complete problems are not in BQP either.

So, even in theory (without considering physical constraints), quantum computers cannot solve EXPTIME-complete problems in polynomial time because these problems are provably beyond the class PSPACE, and quantum computation is contained within PSPACE.

To summarize the chain of reasoning:

1. BQP ⊆ PSPACE (proven)

2. PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME (proven)

3. PSPACE ≠ EXPTIME (proven by the hierarchy theorems) → so PSPACE ⊊ EXPTIME

4. Therefore, BQP ⊊ EXPTIME (so BQP does not contain EXPTIME-complete problems)

Hence, no quantum computer (operating within the BQP model) can solve an EXPTIME-complete problem in polynomial time.
